1
00:00:00,200 --> 00:00:04,430
In this video we are going to learn vertical slice architecture.

2
00:00:04,790 --> 00:00:08,480
Vertical slice architecture introduced by Jaime Bogaerts.

3
00:00:08,480 --> 00:00:15,560
And it offers this architecture against two traditional layered onion clean architecture approaches.

4
00:00:16,070 --> 00:00:22,790
Vertical Slice Architecture aims to organize code around specific features or use cases, rather than

5
00:00:22,790 --> 00:00:26,630
the technical concerns in a vertical slice architecture.

6
00:00:26,660 --> 00:00:33,260
A feature is implemented across all layers of the software, from the user interface to the database.

7
00:00:34,100 --> 00:00:40,910
This approach is often used in the development of complex, feature rich applications, particularly

8
00:00:40,910 --> 00:00:43,070
those that are delivered over the web.

9
00:00:43,760 --> 00:00:50,120
Vertical slice architecture is dividing an application into distinct features or functionalities, and

10
00:00:50,120 --> 00:00:54,050
each of them cuts through all of the layers of the application.

11
00:00:54,680 --> 00:01:01,880
This approach is in contrast to the traditional n-tier or layered architectures, where the application

12
00:01:01,880 --> 00:01:03,410
is divided horizontally.

13
00:01:03,920 --> 00:01:10,580
So that means, unlike the traditional n-tier or layered architectures where the application is divided

14
00:01:10,580 --> 00:01:11,480
horizontally.

15
00:01:11,480 --> 00:01:17,090
As you can see, the image, presentation, application and data layers, the vertical slice architectures

16
00:01:17,090 --> 00:01:21,950
divide an application vertically based on the features or functionalities.

17
00:01:22,760 --> 00:01:26,450
So let's see the characteristics of the vertical slice architecture.

18
00:01:26,450 --> 00:01:28,640
Of course, the first characteristic is.

19
00:01:28,640 --> 00:01:32,510
The application is divided into feature based slices.

20
00:01:32,510 --> 00:01:37,730
So the application is divided into slices based on the features or use cases.

21
00:01:37,790 --> 00:01:44,120
Each slice represents a complete vertical pathway through the application stack, including the user

22
00:01:44,120 --> 00:01:51,440
interface, business logic, and data access layers, and each slice is self-contained and independent.

23
00:01:51,800 --> 00:01:58,670
That means each vertical slice is intended to be self-contained and independent from other slices.

24
00:01:58,670 --> 00:02:05,090
This means that a single feature can be developed, tested, and deployed without impacting other parts

25
00:02:05,090 --> 00:02:06,140
of the application.

26
00:02:07,250 --> 00:02:12,860
There are reduced dependencies between different parts of the application by focusing on the vertical

27
00:02:12,860 --> 00:02:17,960
slices, dependencies between different areas of the application are minimized.

28
00:02:17,960 --> 00:02:24,680
Each slice can be seen as a mini application with its own distinct functionality and dependencies.

29
00:02:25,920 --> 00:02:29,250
It promotes the use of the cross-functional teams.

30
00:02:29,250 --> 00:02:35,880
Development teams working with the vertical slice architecture are often cross functional, containing

31
00:02:35,880 --> 00:02:41,880
all the skills necessary to develop a feature from start to finish, which promotes a more holistic

32
00:02:41,880 --> 00:02:47,520
view of the development and the architecture supports scalability and maintainability.

33
00:02:47,550 --> 00:02:51,810
This architecture allows for better scalability and maintainability.

34
00:02:51,870 --> 00:02:58,530
As the application grows, new features can be added as a Neve slices without significantly impacting

35
00:02:58,530 --> 00:03:03,780
the existing code, and also it allows for improved testing and deployment process.

36
00:03:03,810 --> 00:03:10,080
Vertical slices can be individually tested and deployed, which simplifies the testing process, and

37
00:03:10,080 --> 00:03:13,320
it can lead to more reliable and faster deployments.

38
00:03:14,130 --> 00:03:20,160
Vertical slice is an internal application architecture pattern that every microservices can follow.

39
00:03:20,190 --> 00:03:22,590
This architecture in their internal code.

40
00:03:22,590 --> 00:03:24,990
Organizations in the microservices.

41
00:03:25,020 --> 00:03:31,290
Every microservice handle a specific piece of the functionality and communicate with other services

42
00:03:31,290 --> 00:03:33,270
through well defined interfaces.

43
00:03:34,110 --> 00:03:37,440
So let's see the advantages of the vertical slice architecture.

44
00:03:37,470 --> 00:03:41,220
Vertical slice architecture offers several benefits.

45
00:03:41,250 --> 00:03:47,400
It allows for focused development where the teams can concentrate on one feature at a time.

46
00:03:47,430 --> 00:03:54,030
It simplifies refactoring and upgrades, since changes in one slice usually don't affect others.

47
00:03:54,060 --> 00:04:00,480
It aligns well with the agile and DevOps practices, supporting incremental development and continuous

48
00:04:00,480 --> 00:04:01,110
delivery.

49
00:04:01,410 --> 00:04:05,520
However, there are also challenges with using the vertical slice.

50
00:04:05,520 --> 00:04:11,760
You might encounter duplication of code across slices, particularly for common functionalities.

51
00:04:11,760 --> 00:04:18,120
There is a learning curve involved, especially for teams opposed to the traditional architectures.

52
00:04:18,120 --> 00:04:24,990
The design of the each slice requires careful consideration in order to ensure independence and maintainability.

53
00:04:25,350 --> 00:04:32,040
So vertical slice architecture is a powerful approach for developing complex applications where modularity

54
00:04:32,040 --> 00:04:34,020
and rapid development are crucial.

55
00:04:34,020 --> 00:04:39,240
So we will also use vertical slice architecture into our catalog and basket microservices.

